<div id="review_4101763982" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4101763982" />
    <a title="Rami" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20481013-rami"><img alt="Rami" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4101763982?book_show_action=true">Jul 07, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rami" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rami" href="/user/show/20481013-rami">Rami</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4101763982" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer510892115691339563">I don&apos;t read much anymore, and it&apos;s because we&apos;re so inundated with language and linguistic acrobatics that words just seem to be a form of pollution these days.<br/><br/>Yet this is the one text that I keep coming back to, because it&apos;s just so utterly crazy (from a modern perspective) that it de-programs me at a root level. It&apos;s a reminder that how we&apos;re living our lives is actually profoundly unwise given the effects it&apos;ll have: that reaching for our own wellbeing while stepping on others will create th</span>
  <span id="freeText510892115691339563" style="display:none">I don't read much anymore, and it's because we're so inundated with language and linguistic acrobatics that words just seem to be a form of pollution these days.<br /><br />Yet this is the one text that I keep coming back to, because it's just so utterly crazy (from a modern perspective) that it de-programs me at a root level. It's a reminder that how we're living our lives is actually profoundly unwise given the effects it'll have: that reaching for our own wellbeing while stepping on others will create the karma for later dispossession, and other terrifying aphorisms which I've highlighted to use as a whip for my psyche whenever I find myself slipping into spiritual complacency.<br /><br />There's just something magical about this text. The fact that it was the most popular text to come out of Ancient India's Nalanda University is reason enough to read it, but the centrality it took up in Tibet for a thousand years after that just adds fuel to the fire. It's apparently what made the Dalai Lama into the learned person he is today, and it does add a balm to existential wounds in a way that nothing else seems able to. This isn't dry psychology, nor fake deep life advice, but a real manual for stepping onto the Great Path, which requires things of us that popular culture wouldn't dare to even think about, such as behaving like an altruistic phantom, offering up one's own limbs for others, and never losing a mind bent on evolution, even for a moment. It's essentially a how-to guide for sainthood - and there is a 0% chance that you're ready to hear everything that it has to say (which is why you should read it).</span>
  <a data-text-id="510892115691339563" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


