<span id="freeTextContainer12362589638942621457">The good:<br/>1. Brilliant analogies. <br/>2. Sound logic.<br/>3. Genuine wisdom.<br/>4. Practical advice.<br/>The bad:<br/>1. It&apos;s not Buddhism, but rather Shantidevaism.<br/>2. The idea of selfish altruism* i.e. One should accumulate good karma for basically the same reason that a squirrel accumulates nuts.<br/>3. The idea that wisdom is a reifiable and therefore transferable i.e. Bodhisattvaism.<br/>4. Impractical advice.<br/>Note on the translation: Very good but a bit too modern/contemporary for my taste.<br/>*Altruism is defined by Merriam Web</span>
  <span id="freeText12362589638942621457" style="display:none">The good:<br />1. Brilliant analogies. <br />2. Sound logic.<br />3. Genuine wisdom.<br />4. Practical advice.<br />The bad:<br />1. It's not Buddhism, but rather Shantidevaism.<br />2. The idea of selfish altruism* i.e. One should accumulate good karma for basically the same reason that a squirrel accumulates nuts.<br />3. The idea that wisdom is a reifiable and therefore transferable i.e. Bodhisattvaism.<br />4. Impractical advice.<br />Note on the translation: Very good but a bit too modern/contemporary for my taste.<br />*Altruism is defined by Merriam Webster as: "<i>unselfish</i> regard for or devotion to the welfare of others."</span>
